05002nam a22007815i 9780231548038DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019004423  a97802315480387 a10.7312/roge188842doi  a(DE-B1597)526857  a(OCoLC)1084621571  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aPN1993.5.U6 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4309732231 aRogers, Ariel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn the Screen :bDisplaying the Moving Image, 1926–1942 /cAriel Rogers. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b65 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Production Screens in the Long 1930s: Rear Projection and Special Effects -- t2. Theatrical Screens, 1926– 1931: Transforming the Screen -- t3. Theatrical Screens, 1931– 1940: Integrating the Screen -- t4. Extratheatrical Screens in the Long 1930s: Film and Television at Home and in Transit -- tCoda: Multiplicity, Immersion, and the New Screens -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, in a world of smartphones, tablets, and computers, screens are a pervasive part of daily life. Yet a multiplicity of screens has been integral to the media landscape since cinema’s golden age. In On the Screen, Ariel Rogers rethinks the history of moving images by exploring how experiments with screen technologies in and around the 1930s changed the way films were produced, exhibited, and experienced.Marshalling extensive archival research, Rogers reveals the role screens played at the height of the era of “classical” Hollywood cinema. She shows how filmmakers, technicians, architects, and exhibitors employed a variety of screens within diverse spaces, including studio soundstages, theaters, homes, stores, and train stations. Far from inert, screens served as means of structuring mediated space and time, contributing to the transformations of modern culture. On the Screen demonstrates how particular approaches to the use of screens traversed production and exhibition, theatrical and extratheatrical practice, mainstream and avant-garde modes, and even cinema and television. Rogers’s history challenges conventional narratives about the novelty of the twenty-first-century multiscreen environment, showing how attention to the variety of historical screen practices opens up new ways to understand contemporary media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMotion picture industryxTechnological innovations. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/roge1888440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548038423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548038.jpg  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065195-9  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  